  "summary": "The target surveillance week (June 29–July 5, 2026) has ended, and JIHS published the provisional national HFMD figure of 7.03 cases/sentinel on July 14, 2026 — the exact source and metric this question resolves on. The trajectory (2.75→3.40→4.61→7.03 for W24–W27) is internally consistent, with W26=4.61 corroborated by three independent sources, and the +2.42 jump matches the historical W27 acceleration signature. The question resolves to the confirmed figure if published by July 24, else the provisional 7.03. Remaining uncertainty is only the small provisional→confirmed revision (typically a few percent, slightly upward) plus minor single-source transcription risk. Distribution centered tightly on ~7.05.",
  "reasoning": "Forecast submitted.\n\n**Summary:** Japan's national HFMD cases-per-sentinel for Week 27 of 2026 (June 29–July 5) will be **~7.03** cases/sentinel.\n\nThis is an unusually high-confidence numeric forecast because the target week has already ended, and JIHS published the provisional (速報) national figure of **7.03** today (July 14, 2026) — the exact source and metric the question resolves on. The value is well-supported: 15,845 total cases, 27 of 47 prefectures over the 5.0 alert threshold, and a clean, internally-consistent trajectory (2.75 → 3.40 → 4.61 → 7.03 for weeks 24–27), with the W26=4.61 confirmed by three independent sources.\n\nThe only remaining uncertainty is the small provisional→confirmed revision (typically a few percent, slightly upward) and minor single-source transcription risk, so I centered a tight distribution on 7.05:\n- **P10: 6.89 · P50: 7.05 · P90: 7.27**\n\nNotably, 2026 is running well below the 2024 (8.45 at W26) and 2019 (6.70 at W26) seasons, consistent with Japan's biennial HFMD pattern where off-years are milder.",
